# .shellsecretignore — paths to skip during secret_scan (SPEC §6.1).
#
# Format: gitignore-narrow. Each non-comment, non-blank line is a glob.
# - Trailing `/` means "this directory and everything under it" (matched
#   as both `prefix` and `prefix*`).
# - Negation (`!`), `**` recursion, and anchored `/foo` are NOT supported.
# - Case-sensitive. Matched via bash `case` against staged paths.
#
# These defaults reduce false positives on doc/test fixtures that
# legitimately contain plausible-looking secret patterns (example
# READMEs, smoke fixtures, ADR snippets). Real secret-bearing files
# should never live under these paths; if you must put one there,
# escape with `SKIP_HOOKS=secret SKIP_REASON='<why>'` and the audit
# log records it.

# Test files and dirs — smoke fixtures include literal AWS examples,
# password placeholders, and fake tokens to exercise the patterns.
*test*

# Example dirs and files — README snippets, demo configs, fixture
# data. Real secrets must not live in examples.
*example*

# Project documentation — Markdown is prose; password placeholders
# in code blocks are the most common false-positive source.
docs/

# Markdown files anywhere — same rationale as docs/, but covers
# top-level READMEs and ADR-style files outside docs/.
*.md
